{{other uses}} {{Infobox magazine | title = High Times | logo = | logo_size = | image_file = Hightimes-first-issue-1974.jpg | image_size = <!-- (defaults to user thumbnail size if no size is stated) --> | image_alt = | image_caption = Cover image of ''High Times''{{'}} premiere issue, Summer 1974. | editor = Mike Gianakos | editor_title = Editor-in-Chief | editor2 = [[Danny Danko]] | editor_title2 = Senior Cultivation Editor | editor3 = Frank Max | editor_title3 = Art Director | editor4 = | editor_title4 = | editor5 = Sean Cooley | editor_title5 = Content Director | staff_writer = | photographer = | category = | frequency = Monthly | circulation = | publisher = | founder = [[Tom Forcade]] | founded = | firstdate = {{Start date|1974|Summer}} | company = Trans-High Corporation | country = [[United States]] | based = [[New York City]] | language = English | website = {{URL|https://hightimes.com}} | issn = 0362-630X | oclc = }}
'''''High Times''''' is a monthly magazine and cannabis brand with offices in Los Angeles and New York City. The magazine was founded in 1974 by [[Tom Forcade|Tom Forçade]] and the publication advocates the [[legalization of cannabis]]. The magazine has been involved in the marijuana-using [[counterculture]] since its inception.
==Origins== The magazine was founded in 1974 by Tom Forçade of the [[Underground Press Syndicate]].<ref>Danko, Danny. [https://hightimes.com/news/norml-founder-retires-exhale-stage-left/ "Norml Founder Retires – Exhale Stage Left"]. hightimes.com, January 6, 2005. Accessed 11 September 2009.</ref> ''High Times'' was originally meant to be a joke: a single-issue lampoon of ''[[Playboy]]'', substituting weed for sex.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/03/style/high-times-wants-to-be-the-playboy-of-pot.html|title=High Times Wants to Be the Playboy of Pot|last=Williams|first=Alex|date=2016-04-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-03-15|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The magazine was at the beginning funded by drug money from the sale of illegal marijuana.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/high-times-is-moving-to-los-angeles-7831069|title=High Times Is Moving to Los Angeles|last=Romero|first=Dennis|date=2017-01-18|work=L.A. Weekly|access-date=2017-03-15}}</ref> But the magazine found an audience, and in November 2009, celebrated its 35th anniversary.<ref>Krassner, Paul. [http://hightimes.com/lounge/pkrassner/5894 "Tom Forçade: Prisoner of Romance"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091005012208/http://hightimes.com/lounge/pkrassner/5894 |date=2009-10-05 }}. hightimes.com, October 1, 2009.</ref> Like ''Playboy'', each issue contains a centerfold photo; however, instead of a nude woman, ''High Times'' typically features a cannabis plant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kdvr.com/2017/06/02/high-price-paid-for-high-times-magazine/|title=High Price Paid for High Times|publisher=CNN|date=2017-06-02|accessdate=2018-04-06}}</ref>
The magazine soon became a monthly publication with a growing circulation, audited by ABC as reaching 500,000 copies an issue, rivaling ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' and ''[[National Lampoon (magazine)|National Lampoon]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1987-03-30/features/8701240626_1_high-times-anti-drug-magazine|title=What to read if you just don't say 'no'|first=Bob|last=Greene|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=1987-03-30|accessdate=2018-04-06}}</ref> In 2014, its website was read by 500,000 to 5 million users each month.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2014/10/high-times-hits-middle-age.html|title=High Times hits middle age: How the marijuana magazine stays relevant|first=Joe|last=Coscarelli|publisher=New York Magazine|date=2014-10-17|accessdate=2018-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/02/12/high-times-seeks-marijuana-momentum/5292975/|title=For marijuana magazine, high and heady times|first=Roger|last=Yu|publisher=USA Today|date=2014-02-12|accessdate=2018-04-06}}</ref> The staff quickly grew to 40 people. In addition to high-quality photography, ''High Times'' featured cutting-edge journalism covering a wide range of topics, including politics, activism, drugs, sex, music and film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestreet.com/story/14159408/1/high-times-gets-passed-to-first-new-owner-since-1974.html|title=New owner of 'High Times' sees a business ready to be fully baked|first=Leon|last=Lazaroff|publisher=The Street|date=2017-06-02|accessdate=2018-04-06}}</ref> Tom Forçade was quoted as saying "Those cavemen must've been stoned, no pun intended."{{Citation needed|date=March 2017}} Tom Forçade’s previous attempts to reach a wide counterculture audience by creating a network of underground papers (UPS & APS) had failed, even though he had the support of several noteworthy writers, photographers and artists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/1999/10/26/our-buds-ourselves/|title=Our Buds, Ourselves|first=Cynthia|last=Cotts|publisher=Village Voice|date=1999-10-26|accessdate=2018-04-06}}</ref> Yet, through ''High Times'', Forçade was able to get his message to the masses without relying on mainstream media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hightimes.com/legal/kstroup/5916 |title=NORMLizer – Here’s to HIGH TIMES! |last=Stroup |first=Keith |date=October 9, 2009 |work=High Times |access-date=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120527074926/http://hightimes.com/legal/kstroup/5916 |archive-date=May 27, 2012 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hightimes.com/lounge/pkrassner/5894 |title=Brain Damage Control: Tom Forçade: Prisoner of Romance |last=Krassner |first=Paul |date=October 1, 2009 |work=High Times |access-date=March 15, 2017 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120527074925/http://hightimes.com/lounge/pkrassner/5894 |archive-date=May 27, 2012 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
In January 2017, the magazine announced it would be relocated to an office in Los Angeles permanently.<ref name=":0" /> This followed the legalization of marijuana in several west coasts states including California.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.crainsnewyork.com/article/20170112/REAL_ESTATE/170119947/high-times-magazine-leaving-new-york-for-los-angeles|title=High Times magazine is leaving New York for Los Angeles|last=Flamm|first=Matthew|date=January 12, 2017|work=Crain's New York Business|access-date=March 15, 2017}}</ref>
''High Times'' acquired cannabis media company ''Green Rush Daily'' Inc. on April 05, 2018.<ref>http://labusinessjournal.com/news/2018/apr/04/high-times-acquires-green-rush-estimated-69-millio/</ref> The deal was valued at $6.9 million. ''Green Rush Daily'' founder Scott McGovern joined the magazine as Senior Executive Vice President.<ref>https://www.greenmarketreport.com/high-times-acquires-green-rush-daily-in-all-stock-deal/</ref>
==Related endeavors== ===Recognition and award ceremonies=== * The ''High Times'' [[Lester Grinspoon]] Lifetime Achievement Award has been awarded to [[Lester Grinspoon]] (2010), [[Jack Herer]] (2011), [[Keith Stroup]] (2011), Michael and Michelle Aldrich (2011), [[Richard Lee (activist)]] (2012), [[Vivian McPeak]] (2012), [[Dennis Peron]] (2013), [[Rick Steves]] (2013), Chuck Ream (2014), [[Marc Emery]] (2014), Steve DeAngelo (2015), James J. Goodwin (2016) and Subcool (2017). * * Freedom Fighter of the Month awards are awarded monthly in the magazine. * Freedom Fighter of the Year is awarded to an activist annually for extraordinary commitment to the cause of cannabis. Winners include Debby Goldsberry (2011), [[Mason Tvert]] (2012) * Each year ''High Times'' inducts a member of the counterculture, living or deceased, into the [[Counterculture Hall of Fame]] Award (in Amsterdam). * [[STASH Awards]] - Significant Technological Advancements in Secretive Horticulture award (September issues)
