[[de:Möbel#Sitzmöbel]]

{{Labor |expanded=strikes}} A '''sit-down strike''' is a [[labour strike]] and a form of [[civil disobedience]] in which an organized group of workers, usually employed at factories or other centralized locations, take unauthorized or illegal [[Occupation of factories|possession of the workplace]] by "sitting down" at their stations. The attraction for workers of a sit-down strike is that the practice prevents employers from replacing them with [[strikebreaker]]s or removing equipment to transfer production to other locations. [[Neal Ascherson]] has commented that an additional attraction of the practice is that it emphasizes the role of workers in providing for the people, and allows workers to in effect hold valuable machinery hostage as a bargaining chip.{{sfn|Ascherson|1983}}{{verification needed|date=July 2018}}
Workers have used this technique since the beginning of the 20th century in countries such as [[United States]], [[Italy]], [[Poland]], [[Croatia]], and [[France]]. However, sit-down strikes are now uncommon.
==Notable examples== {{Globalize/West|section|date=July 2018}} The radical syndicalist group [[Industrial Workers of the World]] (IWW) were the first American union to use the sit-down strike. On December 10, 1906, at the General Electric Works in [[Schenectady, New York]], 3,000 workers sat down on the job and stopped production to protest the dismissal of three fellow IWW members.{{sfnm |1a1=Dubofsky |1y=2000 |1p=71 |2a1=Watson |2y=2005 |2p=54}} The three fired IWW members were ultimately rehired.{{sfn|McGerr|2010|p=141}}
The [[United Auto Workers]] staged successful{{clarify|date=December 2016}}<!--successful how? --> sit-down strikes in the 1930s, most famously in the [[Flint Sit-Down Strike]] of 1936–1937. In [[Flint, Michigan]], strikers occupied several [[General Motors Corporation|General Motors]] plants for more than forty days, and repelled the efforts of the police and National Guard to retake them. A wave of sit-down strikes followed, but diminished by the end of the decade as the courts and the [[National Labor Relations Board]] held that sit-down strikes were illegal and sit-down strikers could be fired (see the 1939 Supreme Court ruling in [[NLRB v. Fansteel Metallurgical Corp.]]). While some sit-down strikes still occur in the United States, they tend to be spontaneous and short-lived.
French workers engaged in a number of [[occupation of factories|factory occupations]] in the wake of the [[French May|French student revolt]] in May 1968. At one point more than twenty-five percent of French workers were on strike, many of them occupying their factories.{{cn|date=December 2016}}
In 1973, the workers at the [[Triumph Motorcycles Ltd|Triumph Motorcycles]] factory at [[Meriden, West Midlands]], locked the new owners, [[Norton Villiers Triumph|NVT]], out following the announcement of their plan to close Meriden.{{sfn|Brooke|2002|p=148}} The sit-in lasted over a year until the British government intervened, the result of which was the formation of the Meriden Motorcycle Co-operative{{sfn|Brooke|2002|p=148}} which produced Triumphs until their closure in 1983.{{cn|date=December 2016}}
The sit-down strike was the inspiration for the [[sit-in]], where an organized group of protesters would occupy an area in which they are not wanted by sitting and refuse to leave until their demands are met.
